{
  "text": "The amount of cell protein for each cell sample in the kinetic and oxygen consumption studies (Figs. 1-6 and 9), as measured at the end of the experiments using the Bio-Rad protein assay following sonication in H 2O as described above, was normalized to its respective microcarrier bead surface area, obtained by drying and weighing the beads. The values obtained, in microgram of protein/cm 2 surface area, for the normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cell samples, were 34.1 Ϯ 1.0 (means Ϯ SE; n ϭ 121) and 36.2 Ϯ 1.0 (means Ϯ SE; n ϭ 121), respectively, with no significant differences between the two cell types (P Ͼ 0.05, t-test). For the kinetic studies in Figs. 1-6, there were also no detectable differences between normoxic and hyperoxiaexposed cells with respect to the total cell LDH activities normalized to microcarrier bead surface area (units/cm 2 ), which were 88.5 Ϯ 2.4 (means Ϯ SE; n ϭ 119) and 88.6 Ϯ 2.0 (means Ϯ SE; n ϭ 119), respectively, or the total cell LDH activities normalized to cell protein (units/mg), which were 2.8 Ϯ 0.1 (means Ϯ SE; n ϭ 119) and 2.6 Ϯ 0.1 (means Ϯ SE; n ϭ 119), respectively. These observations provided the basis for normalization of experimental data to cell-coated microcarrier bead surface area (cm 2 ). Statistical comparisons between groups were carried out using the Student's t-test, and the multiple comparison for equality of the slopes of the linear regressions of baseline KCN-insensitive oxygen consumption was performed using analysis of covariance, as in Ref. 72 . Figure 1 , A and C, shows the DQ concentrations in the medium surrounding normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cells, respectively, after addition of 50 M DQ or DQH 2 . For both the normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cells, the DQ concentration in the medium decreased with time when DQ was added and increased with time when DQH 2 was added, the latter of which could not be accounted for by the relatively slow rate of DQH 2 autooxidation determined in a previous study [CITATION_1] . By ϳ15 min, the medium DQ concentrations approached steady states that were independent of whether DQ or DQH 2 was initially added but were ϳ4.5 times lower in the medium surrounding the hyperoxia-exposed cells than the normoxic cells. As shown in Fig. 1, B and D, the DQH 2 concentrations in the medium removed from the cells at the end of the 30-min incubation were ϳ3.5 times higher in the medium surrounding the hyperoxia-exposed than the normoxic cells and were also reasonably independent of whether DQ or DQH 2 was initially added. Fig. 2 . DQ-mediated ferricyanide reduction by normoxic and hyperoxiaexposed cells. Shown is the ferrocyanide concentration generated vs. time after addition of ferricyanide (600 M) and DQ (50 M) to the normoxic or hyperoxia-exposed cells. Also shown is the ferrocyanide concentration vs. time when ferricyanide was incubated with cells in the absence of DQ. The latter was subtracted as background from data obtained in the presence of DQ. Experiments were carried out as sets of normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cells, with each set from the same cell passage studied on the same day. The surface areas of cell-coated microcarrier beads (means Ϯ SE in units of cm 2 ) used for the normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cell studies in the presence of DQ were 50.6 Ϯ 1.9 and 51.3 Ϯ 2.3, respectively, and 55.1 Ϯ 3.6 and 45.6 Ϯ 4.3, respectively, in the absence of DQ. The symbols represent the data (means Ϯ SE) from n ϭ 16 each of the normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cell studies with DQ and n ϭ 4 each without DQ. The solid lines represent linear regression fits to the ferrocyanide vs. time data. Fig. 1 . Duroquinone (DQ) concentrations in the medium surrounding normoxic (A) and hyperoxia-exposed (C) cells during incubation with 50M DQ (F) or durohydroquinone (DQH2; E). The DQ concentrations were determined spectrophotometrically as described in MATERIALS AND METHODS. Experiments were carried out as sets of normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cells, with each set from the same cell passage studied on the same day. B and D: after 30 min of incubation, the medium was removed from the normoxic or hyperoxia-exposed cells, respectively, and peroxidase and H2O2 were added to the cell-free medium. The reappearance of DQ, indicated by the arrows, reflects the DQ generated via the peroxidase-catalyzed oxidation of DQH2, and thus provides a measure of the DQH2 concentration that was in the medium surrounding the cells at 30 min in A and C, respectively. The surface areas of cell-coated microcarrier beads (means Ϯ SE in units of cm 2 ) used for the normoxic cell studies in A were 50.2 Ϯ 3.4 and 53.6 Ϯ 2.4, for DQ and DQH2 additions, respectively, and for the hyperoxia-exposed studies in C were 52.0 Ϯ 2.1 and 48.1 Ϯ 3.4, for the DQ and DQH2 additions, respectively. The symbols represent the data (means Ϯ SE) for n ϭ 9 each for the DQ additions and n ϭ 10 each for the DQH2 additions for the normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cells. The lines represent the model fit to the data, as described in Data analysis.",
